 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kurley>Kurley</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 609<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/28/03 10:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1471.topic&index=58>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_star.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: More trivia...</span><hr size=1> Ahhh you're dredging up some good old stuff here and I'll take the liberty to expand on and correct some of what you've stated:<br>
<br>
The Village of Homlet - one of the very first AD&amp;D modules and it was created as the springboard for a number of other modules for 1st Ed...which were all based in the World of Greyhawk, although the official worldbook was released after a number of modules had come out.<br>
<br>
Temple of Elemental Evil - went through a number of iterations until it became the meatgrinder it was in its original release.<br>
<br>
Into the Halls of the Frost Giant Jarl (the exact title may be incorrect) - actual title was the Glacial Rift of the Frost Giant Jarl.  Originally released as three individual modules (&quot;The Steading of the Hill Giant Chief&quot;, &quot;The Glacial Rift of the Frost Giant Jarl&quot; and &quot;Hall of the Fire Giant King&quot;) the module was rereleased as &quot;Against the Giants&quot;.  It is in the Hall of the Fire Giant King that drow were first introduced into D&amp;D, their appearance which moved the Against the Giants series underground into the Drow/Lolth series.<br>
<br>
Shrine of the Kuo Toa - part of the Drow/Lolth series and originally released on its own, Shrine of the Kuo Toa was rereleased as &quot;Descent Into the Depths of the Earth&quot; with additional information which tied it into the Drow series.<br>
<br>
Vault of the Drow (early drow module, possibly the start of the Salvatorean Forgotten Realms era) - this module had nothing to do with Forgotten Realms (as the Drow/Lolth series was based in Greyhawk) nor with R.A. Salvator.  However it set the course and fleshed out the majority of what became Drow mythos.  Gary Gygax really did have some creativity and knew his shit.<br>
<br>
Queen of the Demonweb Pits (also one of the earliest drow modules) - the culmination of the &quot;Against the Giants&quot; series and the Drow series (Descent Into the Depths of the Earth and Vault of the Drow) where players must face off against Lolth, Demon Queen of Spiders and the Drow.  Awesome module.  Reading it you get the sense that the players are tip-toeing along a razor's edge.<br>
<br>
Ravenloft (the first module, not the later sequels) - Best. Module. Ever.<br>
<br>
&quot;Space Jammer (this one was total crap, it was a SciFi offshoot from the World of Greyhawk, and was a cheap attempt to add SciFi into D&amp;D, but I was not the DM, I was only talked into playing this module by a friend  )&quot; <br>
<br>
It was called Spelljammer and didn't necessarily come from Greyhawk.  Spelljammer arose because a number of D&amp;D campaigns (including &quot;official&quot; campaigns run by TSR bigwigs such as Gygax) had ventured into other game worlds (namely Gamma World and Boot Hill) and thus Spelljammer was a means of easing the transitions between the D&amp;D fantasy world and the scifi of Gamma World or the old west of Boot Hill or whatever the hell else a DM wanted.  But I agree - Spelljammer was total crap.<br>
<br>
You forgot to mention a few other oldies but goldies:<br>
<br>
Secret of the Saltmarsh, Danger at Dunwater and The Final Enemy - just a brilliant series of modules that develops like a great detective/mystery novel into a chilling horror story.<br>
<br>
The Lost Caverns of Tsjocanth - probably the best dungeon crawl module ever designed.  I ran this module or variants of it a few times and pretty much everyone always died.<br>
<br>
The Forgotten Temple of Tharizdun - a masterpiece in terms of setting an eerie, desolate mood where your players find much more than they expected.<br>
<br>
The Tomb of Horrors - just plain nasty.  This module is what DM's would pull out of the drawer when they wanted to get rid of players.<br>
<br>
Ahhh, memory lane.<br>
